Title: Fraternity Park, Havana, Cuba
Summary: Cuban telephone co. bldg. in the background. As a remembrance of the VI Pan-American Conference, the Fraternity Tree was planted in this square, which has taken this name. Secretary of P.W., Mr. Cespedes, has made great success in planning this handsome square of Parisian lines built in the tropics, with tropical gardens and plants and colonial details. Havana is continually beautifying herself: this is only the start. Sooner or later Havana will be the prettiest city of all of the Americas. Come again.

Title: Alturas de Almendares Park, Havana, Cuba
Summary: Newer portion of Havana is well designed with broad streets, beautiful promenades, drives and picturesque parks or plazas. About 50 fountains throughout the city are supplied by an aqueduct, which also furnishes water to residences.

Title: U.S.S Maine Monument, Havana, Cuba
Summary: Built by the people of Cuba in grateful memory of the crew of the ill-fated U.S. Battleship Maine, which was blown up in the harbor of Havana, Feb., 1898. This catastrophe was an important factor in causing the United States to assist Cuba in her war for independence.

Title: Capitol Building, Havana, Cuba
Summary: The Capitol Building is a marvel of Engineering, Sculpture, and Painting. Built at a cost of over sixteen million dollars it represents everything modern in construction and is considered the most beautiful palace in Latin America. One of the greatest features in the interior is the enormous statue representing Cuba.

Summary: With a gentle, sloping beach of pure white sand, clear blue water, a good restaurant, dancing pavilion, comfortable dressing rooms and all modern conveniences, it is one of the most delightful bathing resorts in the world.

Title: Morro Castle, Havana, Cuba
Summary: This fine old fortress of solid stone was built in 1587 by Philip II of Spain of whiom it was said: "the Sun never sets on his dominions." In 1762 the English attacked Havana and this fort made a glorious defense, being assaulted by land. The tower was built in 1844 for a lighthouse. Morro Castle being no longer needed as a fortress, is now used as a Military Academy.
